Languages as a professional choice are now valued at the same level as real sciences as natural sciences, technology, engineering and mathematics on the curriculum for primary schools and elsewhere.
A survey conducted by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014 showed that for the reasons employers reported having trouble occupying a vacancy position, 17 percent could be attributed to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly important to prepare young people for a future career.
As more and more job opportunities require language skills, these skills become decisive in a globalized world.
If you have learned a second language, these lifelong skills will provide real benefits in the future, no matter what career you choose.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically give a multilingual person a competitive advantage.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation, and French was the only two-digit language that could speak a number of participants (15 percent).
