Ri reiterated renowned North Korean complaints of Washington's resistance to a gradual nuclear disarmament, where North Korea is rewarded for gradual disarmament, but his declaration was significant because it did not reject unilateral nuclear disarmament completely, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump issued in Singapore on June 12, at the very first meeting between a sitting president of the United States and a North Korean leader, where Kim pledged to work against “nuclear disarmament of the Korean Peninsula” while Trump guaranteed North Korea’s security.
North Korea has called for a formal end to the Korean War that lasted from 1950-53, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first release its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also opposed calls to reduce strict international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'nuclear disarmament first', lifting pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal by coercion, and even opposes 'the declaration of the end of the war'," Ri said.
“The belief that sanctions can force us to kneel is a dream for people who don’t know anything about us.
