A new course at Harvard University this year is aimed at helping students get more sleep by tackling the growing culture of bumping through the night with coffee drinks as fuel.
One academic found that students at the world’s best university often had no idea how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, prepared the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He started the course after he gave a lecture on the impact sleep deprivation has on learning.
“After the lecture, a girl came to me and said, ‘Why has no one said this before?’
She said no one had ever told her how important sleep was, and it surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which starts this year, explains to students how important it is to have good sleep habits in order to be able to perform academically and athleticly, and for the general condition.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and the university's director of health care, said that the university decided to start the course after seeing students suffer from severe sleep deprivation.
The course, which lasts for one hour, has a series of interactive tasks.
In one part, there is a picture of a room in a bedroom, where students can click on coffee cups, curtains, running shoes and books and hear about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep, and how important it is with a sleep routine.
In another section, participants learn how long-term lack of sleep can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer.
A map of campuses with interactive icons makes participants think about their own daily routine.
“We are aware that this is not going to change the behavior of students immediately.
But we believe that they have the right to know about this, just as you have the right to know about the risk of smoking,” said Professor Czeisler.
There is still some pride in being able to puke all night, he said, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students led to sleep deprivation was an increasing problem.
Enough and good sleep should be students’ “secret weapons” against stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said – even as a means of weight gain, as lack of sleep puts the brain in hunger mode, leading to constant hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old from California who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler prepare the course. He took one of the classes to the professor last year, his first year at Harvard.
He said that the course inspired him to work for a course that was available for the entire campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all master’s students to take a similar study program before enrolling at the university.
